dataset.title: Grand Teton and Yellowstone National Parks Herpetological Inventory 2000-2003- Data Package

abstract.para: Supported by the U.S. Geological Survey and the National Park Service Inventory and Monitoring program an amphibian and reptile inventory was conducted in Grand Teton (GRTE) and Yellowstone (YELL) National Parks from 2000-2003. The work consisted of surveying more than 150 sites in 13 catchments in GRTE and 466 sites in 19 catchments in YELL. The project had three main components: systematic surveys, targeted species surveys, and apex monitoring at a long-term study area. The project provided the first systematically collected amphibian occurrence data for the two parks and included remote areas where amphibians had not previously been documented. The study resulted in an updated list of herpetofauna in the parks, species distribution data, and amphibian disease information. Both ranavirus and chytrid fungal disease were present in amphibian populations in YELL.

description.para: This amphibian and reptile inventory involved three main components: systematic surveys, targeted species surveys, and apex monitoring at a long-term study area. Systematic amphibian surveys involved randomly-selected watershed units being surveyed as potential breeding habitat with 2000 serving as the pilot study year. In 2000 and 2001, hydrological units were selected as survey sites. For 2002 and 2003 YELL was partitioned into 10 rectangular blocks and GRTE into 5 blocks. Within each block, a catchment (watershed unit) was randomly selected from pre-established lists until one with potential breeding sites was confirmed. If the catchment has 10 or fewer potential breeding sites (ponds, wetlands, etc.), adjacent catchments were added on until there were 11-50 potential breeding sites within the unit. Surveys of these sites followed standard amphibian encounter methodology (Thoms and Olson 1997). Field crews walked water body perimeters and transects using dip-nets to looks for larvae in the water. This work was completed from June-August of each year. In 2002 and 2003, 18% and 22% of sites respectively were revisited to collect data on detectability of species. The second component of the study was targeted species surveys. The goal was to document the presence of species previously recorded in the park, expected to occur in the park, or which have an uncertain status. For boreal toads the focus was to determine if previously identified breeding sites were still active. Leopard frog searches were conducted in areas where sightings had previously been reported in GRTE and in areas where they could potentially be found in YELL, though there are no records of leopard frogs ever being reported in YELL. Spadefoots were targeted in YELL, but no animals were found. Reptile surveys were conducted in known and suspected areas of activity and incidental sightings during amphibian surveys were also recorded. The third component of the study was an apex monitoring site at Lodge Creek where Columbia spotted frog populations have been monitored since the 1950s. Breeding site and capture/recapture protocols were followed for all three years of this inventory. Additionally, the proportion of frogs showing abnormalities was estimated and water samples were taken. At this time, the spotted frog population at Lodge Creek was the most consistently monitored amphibian site in the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem, providing sufficient data to document annual fluctuations in reproductive effort and population structure. While reviewing these methods and raw data, data quality was evaluated for fields pertaining to geographic coordinates, taxonomy, and sampling event dates. Data quality fields, listed as [FieldName]_flag, have been appended to the dataset to inform data use and communicate any uncertainty that may exist regarding the quality of geographic, taxonomic, and temporal data. Where possible, data not meeting data quality standards were corrected. References: Thoms, C, C. C. Corkran, and D.H. Olson. 1997. Basic amphibian survey for inventory and monitoring in lentic habitats. In Sampling Amphibians in Lentic Habitats. D.H. Olson, W.P. Leonard, and R..B. Bury, eds. Northwest Fauna 4. Society for Northwestern Vertebrate Biology, Olympia, WA.
